description.text:
This is a very useful model - at least to me!

It's a writing pad holder meant to hold a standard 5"x8" writing pad on a refrigerator. It can be used for various notes, lists, or whatever! These notebooks are very affordable and can often be found in multi packs for just a few dollars. The pen folder is large enough to hold a sharpie sized pen so, most pens and pencils should fit without an issue.

Assembly

Assembly is simply done by using super-glue to join the parts. There are slots on the sides to accommodate the pad holders. The back side has my logo so make sure to glue the pad holders in the right direction - so that the pad is held on the FRONT side. The back also has indents to accommodate foam tape for sticking onto a clean flat surface.

Future

I would like to change the base so that the back side is more of a honey-comb. I designed it in openSCAD and I'm not sure how to do that yet. Current design takes a few hours to print the base and uses more filament than it really needs to. Although, its not that bad since it's only 2mm thick.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad.

These are a 9 tooth pinion with 1/4" flattened hub for an aluminum hub made from 1/4" round. You can drill the aluminum to fit the motor shaft and make a set screw to hold it in place. The other gears are a 27 tooth input idler, a 30 x 15 tooth compound gear and a 30 tooth output gear with 1/4" square socket for locking to an output shaft. These are about 1-3/4" diameter gears with robust will made teeth for actual useful torque. I make my gears from PLA, for hardness and rigidity.

I designed them

I create the gears with a gear generator into which I set the gear properties. This then exports the gear drawing as a 2D DXF file into my AutoCad for final tweaking. I then export that drawing to 3D Design and create the 3d model setting thickness, hubs, etc. 3D Design then delivers the G-Code for my printer. Easy..

description.text: This is a self-contained pot for pygmy Sundews. It is 110 mm tall x 73 mm long by 50 mm wide. The walls are 2.5 mm thick, and the inside of the main pot has a radius of 22.5 mm and a height of 102.5 mm. The off-tank is 90 mm deep with a radius of 22.5 mm on the inside. Notes:

200 degrees Celsius on the extruder, and 50 degrees Celsius on the hot plate, decreasing to 30 as the print progresses. 1.75 mm PLA filament was used.

Modify to your own disgression.

There may be some filament in obviously errant areas, I assume depending on the printer and the specifics of the settings. Just cut it off, or sand down if you care that much. Probably isn't necessary.

Outside of an attempt to go for style points, as well as satisfying the criteria of having a secondary water tank that feeds directly into the bottom of the pot, the only real decision that had to be made was figuring out how to waterproof the thing. Here's what's interesting; with my print settings, at least, the sides of an object are perfectly water-tight, but the flat bottoms of things aren't. So, hard problem, smartass solution: don't have any horizontal bottoms. The main tank has a conical bottom, and the water tank has a slanted bottom.

My printer is jammed at the moment, so I haven't had a chance to print this off in time for the Switch launch, but I made these badges of the Nintendo Switch JoyCons in the grip that the internet has decided looks so dog like.

It's a 2 part print, with the tongue being a piece you can insert in. I hope it fits together, but I haven't had a chance to make a test yet. I won't be able to for the next few weeks, but I'd love to see if anyone can make one! I put the flat piece on the back of the model to attach a pin backer to as well.

My wife and I walk to the beach regularly and I never know what to expect when we arrive: low tide, high tide or in between? Each has it's own character. Low tide, for instance, reveals the remains of a shipwreck. When we embark on a walk I want to know. I wanted a tide clock.

Searching for a tide clock revealed a simple clock mechanism that could be calibrated to any tide cycle. Sold! The creator is Nick Sayor of Geppetto Electronics who sells Crazy Clocks on Tindie (https://www.tindie.com/products/nsayer/crazy-clock/). I bought one for tides, perhaps the least "crazy" of his selection, with the expectation that I'd create an appropriate housing around it. The result is this project.

Laser Cut

This project is made from two sheets of acrylic (mirror and blue). The first cut of the mirror acrylic is an etch of two wave patterns, the hole for the clock mechanism, and the outer circle of 5.5". The second cut removes the middle of the blue acrylic with the two 3-wave patterns, top and bottom, and the outer circle of 6".

Final prep before assembly included painting: 1) the clock's "tide hand" red and 2) the etched wave pattern blue. Paying careful attention to centering and orientation, the mirror acrylic is mounted behind the blue acrylic and secured with hot glue around the perimeter. After hardening, the clock mechanism can be inserted and secured and the tide hand is mounted.

I chose a mirrored surface as my back layer, etched waves, and painted the etch blue.

Bearing fits can vary.. not so much the outer diameter, but the inner can be specified by C0-C5 (C3 is typical). When I printed the original, the caps were very loose. These fit nice and snug. Also the way a bearing works is the inner race is slightly wider the outer race, and you should only touch the inner race. Simple live box trap parts. Design is scalable and just build the box to suit what ever you want to trap.
Few Hints

  1. The lever release is designed to angle towards the back to help with the release.
  2. The lever release and the trap door will need to be notched as in the picture to get the release tension just right for your preference.
  3. On the latch you will notice a small loop to turn the trap into a remote release. Just disconnect the side spring with the top spring. Takes just a second. Just hook a line through the guide and to the loop.
    *** The release is now here. It is just a simple drop on attachment that you put on top of the trap when you want to use the remote release. I found even with almost no tension on the spring it could snap the trap release arm. Notice in the picture that there is no tension on the top spring now. Also I glued a foam pad about an inch thick to avoiding, which could loosen the hinges over time slamming too hard.
  4. The picture should be enough to build the basic box. The one in the picture is 18 inches long and its a good rabbit size.
  5. The top release and lever are obvious to put together as you will just need a 5mm pin to drop into the slot and through the lever. The lever should be friction less in it's movement.
  6. The top hinge fits into a 1 1/8 inch hole. so the round part is oriented down and the slot for the 5mm pin faces up. You just assemble it before screwing it down. I will become obvious.
    If there are more questions about how things go just ask and I'll try and hopefully make it easier. I just build them but can't write an instruction manual worth a darn.
    On the latch and spring anchors I made it High .1mm with 50% infill as the first try on the latch the post broke so I made the post bigger and more infill. I just tinker them I am not a structural engineer. ;)
    Some new files
    A. 1/2 hardware cloth accessories if you want to make the box out of hardware cloth

title: Mounting Adapter for Manfrotto 504PLONG sliding plate

description.text: Allows you to mount a camera equipped with a Manfrotto 504PLONG sliding plate onto other camera supports without removing plate.

This Project comes with four printed components. These are:

  1. The mount.
    This is that main body of the unit, into which the plate will slide

  2. The button
    This controls the safety detent that holds the camera plate into the mount until released.

  3. The clamp
    This allows you to immobilize the plate at the proper balance point

  4. The base
    This holds all moving parts permanently in place after assembly.

Other non-printed parts include the following

  1. Mounting nut and turn clamp. Suggested hex nut would be #10-32 with a 3/4" clamping knob
  2. Small tripod mounting screws and nuts 1/4" 20, various lengths as needed. Nuts and bolts should match elongated hex patter on mount.
  3. Large tripod mounting screws 3/8" 16, various lengths as needed. Nuts and bolts should match hex pattern on mount.
  4. The spring from any standard ballpoint pen.
  5. A Manfrotto 504PLONG sliding tripod plate or aftermarket equivalent.

The thing file should be measured to scale exactly. If you are sizing the individual .stl files, start by allowing the program to re-cale the files, then hit the inches to millimeter conversion button and then scale them up at 158.75%

Assembly Instructions:

  1. When all components are printed, carefully clean excess plastic from the mount, particularly where the button will be inserted. The button slides in from the underside with the side notch fitting into the appropriate slot. The pen spring should be placed on the peg and pressed into the appropriate hole in the mount to provide tension. Do this when it is clear that the pieces fit together and slide freely. When the spring is in place, the button should pop into the out position when not pressed. The hump should extend above the floor of the mount and catch the plate as it slides in. The plate should not be able to slide back out without the button pressed, nor should it slide forward out of the mount under any circumstances.

  2. Before installing the clamp, first screw in the turn bolt to remove any excess plastic from inside the hole. Then loosen the bolt untill the slot for the hex nut is clear. Hold the hex nut in place inside it's slot and tighten the bolt. the nut should be close to flush with the side of the mount leaving plenty of room for the clamp. Slide the clamp down over the peg in such a way that the slanted edge of the clamp matches the side of the mount. When properly installed, the plate should slide easily into the mount when the turnbolt is loose, but should be imobile when the turnbolt is snug.

  3. Clean all excess plastic off the base piece before lining it up with the underside of the mount. The large rectangular area should fit into the clamp area on the mount. When installed, the hex nut and clamp should be maintained in their appropriate positions. When the base is snapped into place with all fittings, the button and spring should move freely, but be kept in place. No glue should be necessary to hold the unit together, but this can be added to the mounting pegs at the corners if desired. Do not apply glue to areas where moving parts may be affected.

  4. when mounting the unit to teleprompters, cranes, and other accessories, be sure to use substantial bolts that fit the guides. Both positions are recommended for stability. Use PLA material or other strong plastic. The structure should provide enough strength to hold a typical video camera under normal circumstances and normal use, but beware of mounting extremely heavy cameras, unbalanced loads, or situations where there is undue torque. Remember also that PLA can bend over time under pressure or shrink if subjected to heat. For this reason I DO NOT recommend mounting a camera upside-down, particularly not for long periods of time unattended.

You may choose to print the moving parts in different colors from the base and mount for easy visibility of the mounting direction.

title: Wemos D1 Mini Light switch servo mount (IOT project)

description.text:
I really, really dig the light switch mount plate for an SG90 servo to activate a light switch. I have a bunch of smart bulbs for my other lights, but my kitchen lights are the long, giant, bright bulbs. Phillips' Hues don't really come in that size ;) So I wanted to activate the servo with MQTT (from a RPi running Home Assistant and Mosquitto MQTT server) using a Wemos D1 Mini. I know you're generally supposed to power servos from their own power supply and not the boards, but I figure quick activation are fine. Plus the 5V may be straight from the USB before the regulator for the Wemos D1 Mini, I need to look into it. Regardless, it should be fine. I took the D1 mini case file and combined it with the plate. The thing is not heavy at all, my light switch screws don't even feel the burden. Then I modded the case lid to make room to hide all the wires from the servo and D1 Mini. I also had to trim the press fit sections to be a bit smaller, and the GPIO holes to be a bit wider/longer.

Quick to activate, low cost (already had the servo from a starter kit, bought a bunch of D1 Minis and we all have 3d printers, right?) this thing is awesome. I ran out of white filament on the unmodded versions though... sadface. I included the arduino sketch I used to program the Wemos, and the solidworks file for the lid. Enjoy!

Still, I think it's a handy addition to the "canon" of Altoid inserts. This one is custom made for owners of the Kodama Trinus 3D printer. The Trinus is nearly all black, and its enclosure is made of smoked plastic, so if you need to open your extruder to clean out a block, it's easy for one of the extruder's little black fasteners to bounce off to where you won't find it.

This organizer will help you keep spare fasteners organized (or just stash the ones you've temporarily removed in a way that they won't easily get lost). Oh, and there's room for your tools, too -- small Allen (hex) wrenches, the all-important 5.5mm open-ended wrench for calibration adjustments, etc.

Note that this insert is designed to just barely fit inside an Altoids tin. You'll need to apply pressure to get it into the tin; after that, it's a permanent addition (hope you like it!).

title: Headphone Stand (better than Makerbot's)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I saw Makerbot's headphone stand and thought that it wasn't very good looking or big enough. So I decided to make a 'better' headphone stand.

INSTRUCTIONS: There are three options.
1 - Folding Headphones: Print it in one piece to fit your bed - which may not be large enough for standard headphones. This is based on a 200x200mm print bed. Scaling to a 300x300mm print bed may be large enough to fit standard headphone sizes.

2 - Print Headphone_Stand-Tall.stl which should be tall enough for your headphones. This may be taller than your printer build area, so it is obviously dependent on your printer.

3 - Non-Folding Headphones: Print the 4 parts separately then glue together. The 4 separate parts are scaled larger to be big enough to fit standard headphones when assembled.
You may have to scale the file down to fit your print bed.

Orient the face you want to print on - Cura flatten to bed is located in the rotation menu. Simplify 3D flatten to bed is located in the edit menu (ctrl-L or apple-L). Other slicers... I don't know.

There are two main faces to print from. The easiest would be the back face. If you have amazing bridging capabilities on your printer then you can print it on the bottom face.

Print, use, enjoy!

title: Raspberry Pi and Camera Mount for Nova Labs Prusa i3

description.text:
Combination webcam and Raspberry Pi mount for my Nova Labs Prusa i3. This is a mashup of a thing I designed to work with two other things. I included the files it was designed to work with, should the worst happen and those things go missing at some point.

It mounts using three of the existing frame screws and one additional hole you'll need to drill in in the middle-front for an additional 6/32 screw. It was designed for a BG8 printer. It possibly works for all other BG6 through BGX printers as well. I'm just not sure how much the front portion of the frame was redesigned between versions, if at all.

I used some M3x20 cap head machine screws (not exactly the right application, but it worked very well) to attach the RPi "top" to secure the RPi to the platform. I needed a 12in ribbon cable to for the Raspicam. The 6" cable it comes with worked temporarily, but it was a really tight fit.

The platform/camera mount was originally designed to use a cut-down shaft from an arrow (a few bucks from Walmart or Dicks/Cabelas/BassPro/etc), but I happened to have an M8 threaded rod which screw-fit perfectly.

The LEDs are 12 volt 194/168 style car LEDs. The exact ones I used are here, but in theory any should work. Since they are 12V and I have a 24V power supply, I wired them in series and they've been working that way for close to a year now.

I'm also using a clip-on fisheye lens meant for phones in order to get a little wider field of view (pic included with and without). The exact one I used is here, but in theory any of the same style should work.

Printed in Inland PETG, mostly blue and a little white for the Raspberry Pi cover.

Edit 2017-07-29: Realized that the title was wrong and was for my spool holder instead of this thing. Fixed! It's still working like a champ.

title: Filament Runout Sensor for Marlin and Octoprint

description.text:
Edit Ikea Lack Table Top Mount design added**

This is a mechanical filament sensor which works with every kind of 1.75mm filament. I prefer this endstop instead of an optic sensor which probably may fail with clear filament color.

You should have a Raspberry Pi OctoPrint setup in order to use this sensor with the plugin below. Marlin also has support for filament sensor and you can connect it to ramps or rambo. But if you are using octoprint, sensor should be connected to raspberry otherwise marlin will send M600 comment and if it takes a while to change the filament, host will return a timout and your print will fail.

Marlin:
http://marlinfw.org/docs/configuration/configuration.html#filament-runout-sensor

Watch the video for raspberry pi connection and other details.
http://bit.ly/sensorvideo

Octopi Plugin:
http://bit.ly/sensorplugin

You can buy endstop sensor:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Car-Helicopter-Crash-Collision-Sensor-Impact-Switch-Module-Robot-Model-For-Arduino-with-Dupont-Cable/32294958229.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.5chV7F

Where to mount the sensor?
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2205663 or
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2044085

Put some hot glue between the sensor and the enclosure (size of a pea)

When filament runs out sensor sends the pause command to the printer, if you want you can add M600 command to the pause event on octoprint settings/gcode commands page. So when paused extruder will go to the corner and unload the filament and wait for loading. Check google for M600 command details.

title: X and Y Belt Tensioner for Reach3d

description.text:
X and Y GT2 6mm width belt tensioners to tension belts of all things. You will want to pull the belts taut before sliding the belt into the jaws to secure it. Then you can adjust the screw to further tighten the belts. Your mileage may vary.

The X axis is a bit more specific to the mounting of the Reach3D printer. The idea is that the tensioner pivots in order to distribute even tension on both sides of the belt. This works because the belt wraps around and meets up with itself unlike the Y axis belt.

X Belt Tensioner Parts:
~X-AxisBeltTensionMount
~PivotWheel
~WheelTension
~M3 screw (Hole is sized to self tap)

The Y axis tensioner is basically an end cap for 2020 extruded aluminum so it may work for other printers if your belt ends at the end of the 2020. You'll want to pull the belt taut and slide it into the jaws to hold it in place. I plan to put two on my printer (mirrored), one on each side so that I can tension both sides as evenly as possible and gives me more room to tighten the belt. Also when I installed it, the middle rod broke off. Oops. The 4 T's that slide into the grove should be long enough to keep it stable without the middle rod.

Y Belt Tensioner Parts:
~ 2020BeltTension
~ScrewBlock (Can be omitted if your screw doesn't cut into your belt)
~M5 Screw (Due to how thin the wall is, I opted to use a tap to pre-tap the hole)

Because there is not really room for the sensor on the CTC, putting it outside the edge of the carriage like this needs the soft end stops (travel limits) to be reduced to stop the printer ramming the sensor into the left hand x axis mount.

description.text: Soporte de modulo LRS Dragon V1 sobre emisora 9XR. Permite ser desinstalado en 15 segundos.

This is an adapter to allow ESP-12 modules to be programmed or used with breadboards.

If using lots of these modules then it is good to have a convenient way to mount and use them before any final soldering / integration takes place.

The 3d prints allow spring pins to be used to match the 2mm spacing used on these modules. The pins mate through the holes on the module and allow the module to be just pushed in place. A retaining bar may be used to provide a more secure fit, although for quick programming this may not be needed.

The width of the adapter is kept to a minimum so that when inserted on a breadboard holes are still accessible.

Parts required are 3d printed parts, 16 spring pogo pins (1mm diameter 16mm long, eBay packets of 100), 2 8way single in line jumper posts (cut off longer strips), 2 M3 30mm countersunk screws and nuts.

1) Prepare each pogo pin by soldering a fine wire about 3.5mm up from base. I used 0.2mm wire got from a multistrand cable. It is important that minimal solder is used to keep the final diameter small to avoid shorts when the pins are assembled.

2) Insert the 8 way headers into the base slot with short side up into the pin cavity side. Although a push fit I use a bit of glue to make sure they are secure.

3) Insert pins one at a time into the blind holes in the base and solder the tail onto the header pin.

4) Position pin alignment 3d part over the pins and push down, You can use tweezers to align each pin into the holes as required.

5) insert countersunk screws through both parts and secure with nuts.
